rComments: Gibson is a good presenter, but perhaps not a good instructor. She knows her material well, but talks endlessly for three hours, and basically just repeats the assigned readings without adding anything of substance. Not easily accessible by email or outside of class, but her course is marked fairly and is interesting nonetheless.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Lecture heavy', 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: Prof Gibson is a respectable prof and knows the material well. She usually goes the full three hours, only giving a 5-minute break and doesn't post the slides after class (slides aren't really important for your grade though). A lot of readings, but generally pretty interesting. However, the assignments are graded extremely hard. Final paper 45%

Gibson talks A LOT. It's not bad, but when you're sitting in a cold lecture hall talking about death for 3 hours, it's a little disappointing to only get a 5 minute break at the halfway point (instead of the standard 10-15 minute break for 3 hour lectures). Her guest lecturers were great, added a nice change up (also hello networking opportunity).

Her lectures were amazing. She has so many connections in the field of Bioethics and her guest lectures were amazing! Her lectures alone were also amazing, she has so much insight and really encourages students to participate and formulate their own ideas. lots of reading responses and one final essay. TA was a harsh marker.
Good prof but I feel like the TAs in her courses mark way too hard.

Professor Gibson's lectures are one of a kind, probably the best lectures I've received from my time at UofT. Someone who is so passionate, involved, and very intelligenet about her field of study, Prof Gibson is a gem! Lectures are clear, grading criteria is clear. Only complaint is that she gives out 79 (and does not round it up to 80).
teacherRatingTags: ['Amazing lectures', 'Gives good feedback', 'Get ready to read']
